<subSubSection id="60136D5F1B4D86766DC123481201FA44" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" type="description">
<paragraph id="06AE50DB5F25520707A9A8FFCC66674C" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F93304212E647D1AD3CDAAB08275F352" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">
Perennial climber. Stems up to 1.2 m, likely also longer, glabrous. Petiole 0.7-1.6 cm, glabrous. Leaves 5.2-6 
<normalizedToken id="D98CA6B1BA3115D35B1185CE49F85EBD" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6-7.5 cm, deeply to shallowly 5-lobate, lobes outwards lobulate. Leaf margin remotely dentate, apex obtuse with final tooth. Upper leaf surface glabrous, with clear to whitish pustules. Lower leaf surface glabrous, with glands at base between nerves. Probracts up to 2 mm. Tendrils simple. Male flowers in racemes, accompanied by a solitary flower. Common peduncle 1-1.4 cm, pedicel in racemes 3-6 mm, each glabrous. Bracts up to 1.5 mm, narrowly ovate. Pedicel of solitary flowers 0.9-2 cm, glabrous. Perianth tube glabrous. Calyx lobes 2.5-4 mm, subulate to narrowly triangulate, erect. Corolla c. 2 cm, pale buff, lobes not measured. Filament column, anther head, and pollen sacs not seen. Female flowers solitary or clustered in reduced 2-flowered racemes. Common peduncle 1 mm, pedicel in racemes 0.9-1 mm, pedicel of solitary flower not seen, each glabrous. Hypanthium most likely glabrous and perianth as in male flowers. Ovary glabrous. Style and stigma not seen. Fruit and seeds not seen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4DF4988194AFCFB53BC2C828E3B5811C" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" type="phenology">
<paragraph id="9FF937D39492398893BD6B3CAD8D0C8F" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7A4A777DD129E2D5F05920C1CD1CD585" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">
Flowering time: January-March, November, December. Likely as in 
<taxonomicName id="3016AEA861F1C7BCE2CCFD7D31A90C94" authority="var. sessilifolia" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cucurbitaceae" genus="Coccinia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Coccinia sessilifolia subsp. var. var. sessilifolia" order="Uredinales" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="sessilifolia" subSpecies="var." variety="sessilifolia">Coccinia sessilifolia var. sessilifolia</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5485BB59E47C45D8F1C12AFB5744ED1E" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="2A973C5FDD9612360A4901FF4B2DD8DB" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6DBE73BA737460C7056EBDB338936864" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">
Fig. 
<figureCitation id="67E11E95BCECA136478C1E55919D359E" captionStart="Figure 40" captionStartId="F40" captionText="Figure 40. Distribution map of Coccinia sessilifolia var. sessilifolia (pale yellow dots; based on 133 collections) and Coccinia sessilifolia var. variifolia (blue dots; based on 7 collections). For South Africa the borders of the provinces are given." pageId="117" pageNumber="118">40</figureCitation>
. Only known from Limpopo Province in South Africa. Elevation 800-1200 m. On sandstone, well-drained stony sand. Low closed woodland.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="78757D20255052B583864C034C696C6C" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="82232D2FAD04972C5E0173C6F7E5BDE0" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">
<pageBreakToken id="122F69F3DA7EC7756C55436B56E157E0" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" start="start">Remarks</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="139780EDEBECC0B74E3ECABE93CFC0F5" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">
The new status of 
<taxonomicName id="B5561AAC7AD5149FE81359C8D16606D5" authorityName="Holstein" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Holstein" baseAuthorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cucurbitaceae" genus="Coccinia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Coccinia variifolia" order="Uredinales" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="variifolia">
<emphasis id="6C0F835DE007CC47B1A6B42949B9F543" italics="true" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">Coccinia variifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was chosen due to the minor differences to 
<taxonomicName id="0C909E232FE1C844053E06997AD9B3F9" authorityName="Cogn" authorityYear="1881" baseAuthorityName="Sond." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cucurbitaceae" genus="Coccinia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Coccinia sessilifolia" order="Uredinales" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sessilifolia">
<emphasis id="F0D5EA03C0EA393FFEDA921CD5AFE1BF" italics="true" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">Coccinia sessilifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s.str. Subsessile leaves spontaneously occur in 
<taxonomicName id="61D43F464C6A2DF3D4CB37985093E8E2" authorityName="Cogn" authorityYear="1881" baseAuthorityName="Sond." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cucurbitaceae" genus="Coccinia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Coccinia sessilifolia" order="Uredinales" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sessilifolia">
<emphasis id="85EC6A83E8D00541F0961A3F881481BF" italics="true" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">Coccinia sessilifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis id="88889851AFE6B983849EC1D6F6DE0321" italics="true" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">H. Bolus 364</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="1D7AF7F6811DF1840E60CB544F38E1FC" italics="true" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">F.A. Rogers 19262</emphasis>
) and young individuals usually (always?) have petiolate leaves (
<emphasis id="B85EF52CFD98C1FE6CA0A6EAC7275DEF" italics="true" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">N. Holstein 131</emphasis>
, Fig. 
<figureCitation id="6581D95844B26C0E2A90F6E257D7A4F1" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. a Young plant of Coccinia abyssinica (N. Holstein 132). The first node is in the axilla where the glabrous cotyledons split off. The first nodes lack probracts and tendrils b Young plant of Coccinia sessilifolia (N. Holstein 131). The first leaves in this species are petiolate, sessile leaves are produced later-on. The glabrous cotyledons are already dried (plant had the same age as the one in Fig. 4 a)." pageId="118" pageNumber="119">4b</figureCitation>
). However, these collections of mature plants with distinctly petiolate leaves have only been observed in Limpopo Province in South Africa. Sessile 
<taxonomicName id="73DF650EF118D5A728D4F4FC33DB2F01" authorityName="Cogn" authorityYear="1881" baseAuthorityName="Sond." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cucurbitaceae" genus="Coccinia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Coccinia sessilifolia" order="Uredinales" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sessilifolia">
<emphasis id="755D2A71F1708A66D79C5730BC16FEFA" italics="true" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">Coccinia sessilifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
leaves can be quite variable, profoundly to deeply lobate, sometimes also lobulate. Compared to the rather uniform 
<taxonomicName id="641A242D9CE80FBF51FB6CC25523B272" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cucurbitaceae" genus="Coccinia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Coccinia quinqueloba" order="Uredinales" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="quinqueloba">
<emphasis id="CB17D2006088BA0B7CAA76CD14B22BCE" italics="true" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">Coccinia quinqueloba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="0DC41DBD65E24FF605EDDD8F9881B4CF" author="Meeuse, ADJ" journalOrPublisher="Bothalia" pageId="141" pageNumber="142" pagination="1 - 111" refId="B141" refString="Meeuse, ADJ, 1962. The Cucurbitaceae of Southern Africa. Bothalia 8: 1 - 111" title="The Cucurbitaceae of Southern Africa." volume="8" year="1962">Meeuse 1962</bibRefCitation>
), the leaves thus appear to be extraordinarily variable. 
<normalizedToken id="3592D4F20E529D73C9EA7671FD3537D5" originalValue="Meeuse’s">Meeuse's</normalizedToken>
<taxonomicName id="F7D12FE19D52E74244C21361B457D847" authorityName="Holstein" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Holstein" baseAuthorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cucurbitaceae" genus="Coccinia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Coccinia variifolia" order="Uredinales" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="variifolia">
<emphasis id="F7ADDE7F768B98BCB77F1D4BB56DE611" italics="true" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">Coccinia variifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shares the sublaminal glands (cp. Fig. 
<figureCitation id="433780879E75F2F2A0AFCE17CDE9E45E" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. a Male flower of Coccinia grandis (N. Holstein 37). Apices of the petals and calyx lobes, as well as major teeth on the leaf margin are colored in red. Minor margin teeth are inconspicuously colored. The calyx lobes in Coccinia grandis are spreading in flower buds and reflexed in mature flowers b Male plant of Coccinia sessilifolia. Darkish glands (extranuptial nectaries) are commonly found at the base of a lower leaf lamina. The calyx lobes are unusually large in this specimen (cp. Fig. 2 b)." pageId="118" pageNumber="119">7b</figureCitation>
) and the calyx lobes of 
<taxonomicName id="B03A247315306B3644C4ACE5C762E357" authorityName="Cogn" authorityYear="1881" baseAuthorityName="Sond." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cucurbitaceae" genus="Coccinia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Coccinia sessilifolia" order="Uredinales" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sessilifolia">
<emphasis id="B38B0865169BAF334E4F38211CD6E3F0" italics="true" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">Coccinia sessilifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and it is geographically nested within this species (hence no climatic differentiation). Acocks (
<emphasis id="4FE339A8516A550B1F0744B5C1392CF9" italics="true" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">J.P.H. Acocks 13903</emphasis>
) also reports a &quot;stark glaucous&quot; appearance, just as in 
<taxonomicName id="C1828063E379AE8D31A5EC6D391B3298" authorityName="Cogn" authorityYear="1881" baseAuthorityName="Sond." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cucurbitaceae" genus="Coccinia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Coccinia sessilifolia" order="Uredinales" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sessilifolia">
<emphasis id="F639F3CD6B7D92B53AF0186372718C6C" italics="true" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">Coccinia sessilifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. As petiolate leaves also occur in young 
<taxonomicName id="FD3734EED2754606518DEB9F0C31FE89" authorityName="Cogn" authorityYear="1881" baseAuthorityName="Sond." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cucurbitaceae" genus="Coccinia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Coccinia sessilifolia" order="Uredinales" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sessilifolia">
<emphasis id="D5EEDA716C42860A241721E582814EF0" italics="true" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">Coccinia sessilifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
plants, and subsessile leaves also occur in mature plants, it is more likely that the distinctly petiolate 
<taxonomicName id="89C6FDD0CEC451DE33AE719C4DCFDF94" authorityName="Cogn" authorityYear="1881" baseAuthorityName="Sond." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cucurbitaceae" genus="Coccinia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Coccinia sessilifolia" order="Uredinales" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sessilifolia">
<emphasis id="15C7589875ECD6B7990CBF996A4F8DC4" italics="true" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">Coccinia sessilifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
individuals represent a local fixation of this character. As 
<taxonomicName id="A6CE81C60B41A9DA42DC0646DEE7A50B" authority="var. sessilifolia" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cucurbitaceae" genus="Coccinia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Coccinia sessilifolia subsp. var. var. sessilifolia" order="Uredinales" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="sessilifolia" subSpecies="var." variety="sessilifolia">Coccinia sessilifolia var. sessilifolia</taxonomicName>
is derived from petiolate plants, this variety might even represent a remnant population of these.
</paragraph>
